name: Horizon Enhanced SRI Fossil Fuel Free
summary: The Enhanced SRI Fossil Fuel Free strategy is an all-equity enhanced index strategy. Horizon believes its Enhanced SRI Fossil Fuel Free strategy can achieve outperformance by applying quantitative overlays to the MSCI KLD 400 Social Index, an index that is selected largely on qualitative characteristics, with an added screen that eliminates companies with exposure to fossil fuels. The 40 highest-scoring stocks in the index in terms of Quadrix Overall Score typically make it into the portfolio. Stocks are typically held for 12 months, at which time the equity portfolio is rebalanced and reconstituted depending on the results of our quantitative methodology. Changes to the equities may occur more frequently than annually in the event of takeovers or other corporate actions. For the initial investment selection, no sector can account for more than 25% of the total portfolio. While the portfolio may be 100% invested in stocks, cash and fixed income investments may be held depending on macro market conditions.

name: KBI Emerging Markets ESG Equity Strategy
summary: The KBI Emerging Markets ESG Equity Strategy is a long only manager with a preference towards Emerging Markets equities. The strategy uses a series of exclusionary screens to narrow the investment universe and guide portfolio construction. Step one eliminates companies that do not produce yields above their industry and geographically weighted average. Step two eliminates companies with weak or unsustainable financial fundamentals, as well as the worst performing companies on the MSCI Sustainability Index. Step three involves bottom up research of remaining companies, and a Barra optimization to finalize portfolio weightings. Portfolio targets 25% better ESG scores compared to the index.

name: Knights of Columbus Core Bond Fund
summary: Under normal circumstances, the Fund invests at least 80% of its net assets, plus any borrowings for investment purposes, in bonds. This investment policy can be changed by the Fund upon 60 days' prior written notice to shareholders. For purposes of this policy, bonds include a variety of fixed-income instruments, such as securities issued or guaranteed by the U.S. Government and its agencies or instrumentalities, municipal bonds, corporate obligations, residential and commercial mortgage-backed securities, and asset-backed securities. The Fund invests primarily in U.S. issuers and investment-grade securities, but may hold securities that are rated below investment grade (high yield or junk bonds). The Fund may invest in securities with any maturity or duration. The Fund makes investment decisions consistent with the United States Conference of Catholic Bishops' Socially Responsible Investing Guidelines (the USCCB Guidelines), and therefore, does not invest in companies involved with abortion, contraception, pornography, stem cell research/human cloning, weapons of mass destruction, or other enterprises that conflict with the USCCB Guidelines. In selecting investments to purchase on behalf of the Fund, the Adviser combines quantitative and qualitative analyses to identify market sectors and individual issuers that the Adviser believes are undervalued in the market. For corporate issuers, the Adviser analyzes the company's financial statements as well as its prospects for future cash generation, while for mortgage- or asset-backed securities, the Adviser analyzes the quality of the underlying receivables and structural credit enhancements.  The Adviser will generally sell a security on behalf of the Fund if the security reaches its estimated fair value or is impacted by an adverse event, or if more attractive alternatives exist

name: Loring Ward Global Porfolio Series SRI Conservative
summary:
Benchmark Breakdown: 25% S&P 500, 15% MSCI EAFE (net div), 60% BofAML US Trsy/Agcs AAA 1-3 Yr

The Global Portfolio Series is guided by Loring Ward's Asset Class Investing philosophy, a strategic, asset class investment approach based on the research of some of the academic community's most innovative and respected thinkers and economists. Grounded in the knowledge that asset allocation has the greatest impact on investment returns, Asset Class Investing is designed to carefully control the investments included in each asset class, giving investors truer market returns than similar strategies will. The DFA Funds Global Portfolio Series is built with 5 asset class funds, offered by noted institutional money manager, Dimensional Fund Advisors, and designed to meet the needs of investors looking for investments that serve their social and ethical values and beliefs. The objective of the Conservative portfolio is to provide capital preservation and limited growth by investing in a portfolio of primarily bonds with some stocks. It is designed for those who have a lower tolerance for portfolio fluctuations. The investment time horizon is typically 3 to 5 years or more.

name: Microvest GMG Local Credit Fund
summary:
Investing in emerging market credit assets, predominantly local currency denominated. Investment focus is low-income finance institutions (LIFIs) that provide credit to low-income entrepreneurs. Investment strategy has a 5+ year track record of successfully investing in LIFI credit opportunities. 

LIFIs are solid credit quality institutions, which are profitable and scalable. LIFIs have inefficient access to capital, especially in local currency, which drives attractive risk adjusted returns. LCF offers investors attractive financial returns, plus positive development impact.

summary:

The Global Portfolio Series is guided by Loring Ward's Asset Class Investing philosophy, a strategic, asset class investment approach based on the research of some of the academic community's most innovative and respected thinkers and economists. name: LKCM Aquinas Growth Fund
summary: The Fund seeks to achieve its investment objective by investing under normal circumstances in securities that the Adviser believes generally have above-average growth in revenue and/or earnings, above-average returns on shareholders' equity, and/or potential for above-average capital appreciation. The Fund seeks to invest in the equity securities of high quality companies that typically exhibit certain characteristics, including high profitability levels, strong balance sheet quality, competitive advantages, ability to generate excess cash flows, meaningful management ownership stakes, attractive reinvestment opportunities, strong market share positions, and/or attractive relative valuation. These equity securities may include common stocks, preferred stocks, securities convertible into common stock, American Depositary Receipts (ADRs), real estate investment trusts (REITs), rights and warrants. The Fund may invest in equity securities of small, mid and large capitalization companies. The Fund practices socially responsible investing within the framework provided by the United States Conference of Catholic Bishops' Socially Responsible Investing Guidelines (Guidelines). The Fund's investment approach incorporates the Guidelines through a combination of screening portfolio companies based on criteria set forth in the Guidelines, dialogue with companies whose policies and practices conflict with the Guidelines, and/or potentially excluding from the Fund's portfolio the securities of those companies that are unwilling to alter their policies and practices over a reasonable period of time. The Adviser monitors companies selected for the Fund for policies on various issues contemplated by the Guidelines. If the Fund invests in a company whose policies and practices are inconsistent with the Guidelines, the Adviser may attempt to influence the company or sell the company's securities or otherwise exclude future investments in such company.

name: Parnassus Fixed Income Fund
summary: The Parnassus Fixed Income Fund is an open-end fund incorporated the U.S.A. that normally invests at least 80% of its net assets (plus borrowings for investment purposes) in a diversified portfolio of bonds and other fixed income instruments. Fixed income instruments may include, but are not limited to, U.S. Treasuries and Agency debt, debt of government-related entities, corporate bonds, commercial and residential mortgage-backed securities, convertible bonds and asset-backed securities. The Fund invests mainly in domestic securities, and to a lesser extent may also invest in U.S. dollar denominated foreign securities.  The Fund may purchase foreign securities directly on foreign markets. The Fund's investment adviser (Adviser) also takes environmental, social and governance (ESG) factors into account when making investment decisions. The fund normally invests at least 80% of its net assets in fixed income securities that have investment-grade ratings (namely rated at least BBB- by Standard & Poor's Rating Group (S&P) or at least Baa3 by Moody's Investors Services, Inc. (Moody's)) or, if unrated, have been determined by the Adviser to be of similar economic quality. Additionally, at least 65% of the Fund's total net assets will normally be invested in fixed income securities rated A or better by Moody's or S&P. At any given time, up to 20% of the portfolio may be invested in non-investment grade fixed income securities (otherwise known as high-yield or junk bonds) or unrated fixed income securities determined by the Adviser to be of similar economic quality. Non-investment grade and unrated securities are more risky than investment-grade securities.  The Fund may sell a security if the Adviser believes it no longer meets the Fund's investment objective or if the issuer no longer meets the Adviser's ESG criteria. The Fund may invest in long-term, intermediate-term or short-term fixed income securities or any combination thereof, depending on market conditions, and these securities may also have floating or variable interest rates. As of March 31, 2016, the dollar-weighted average maturity of the Fund's portfolio was 5.37 years.

name: Etho Climate Leadership US ETF
summary:
The ETHO US ETF seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond to the price and yield performance of the Etho Climate Leadership IndexTM (ECLITM), an index of approximately 400 companies with the most climate-efficient and socially responsible profiles within their respective industries (the lowest "Carbon Impact")


"Carbon impact" is calculated based on the total greenhouse gas ("GHG") emissions from a company's operations, fuel use, supply chain and business activities, divided by the company's market capitalization. The Index primarily includes each company with a carbon impact at least 50% better (i.e., lower) than the average carbon impact for a given company's industry ("Carbon Leaders"). The Index generally excludes companies in industries or sub-industries or specific companies that are broadly associated with negative environmental, social, or corporate governance ("ESG") profiles.

name: Loring Ward Global Porfolio Series SRI Captial Appreciation
summary:
Benchmark Breakdown: 51% S&P 500, 34% MSCI EAFE (net div), 15% BofAML US Trsy/Agcs AAA 1-3 Yr

The Global Portfolio Series is guided by Loring Ward's Asset Class Investing philosophy, a strategic asset class investment approach based on the research of some of the academic community's most innovative and respected thinkers and economists. Grounded in the knowledge that asset allocation has the greatest impact on investment returns, Asset Class Investing is designed to carefully control the investments included in each asset class, giving investors truer market returns than similar strategies will. The DFA Funds Global Portfolio Series is built with 5 asset class funds, offered by institutional money manager, Dimensional Fund Advisors, and designed to meet the needs of investors looking for investments that serve their social and ethical values and beliefs. The objective of the Capital Appreciation portfolio is to provide long-term growth, so that those interested in maximizing growth potential and willing to assume a higher level of risk to potentially achieve greater returns. It is Horizon's aim that these investors should have a long-term investment horizon and be able to withstand significant fluctuations in portfolio value. The investment time horizon is typically 15 to 20 years or more.

name: Aperio Total U.S. Market SRI Strategy
summary:
The Total US Market SRI Strategy (the
Strategy) seeks to match the pre-tax
performance of the Russell 3000 Index while
investing in companies that have positive
environmental, social, and governance
(ESG) characteristics. For taxable investors,
the Strategy also attempts to improve aftertax
returns through tax-loss harvesting
techniques.

Exclusions (avoid companies involved in the
following): nuclear weapons, land mines, and
nuclear power as well as those that derive
more than 1% of their revenues from: alcohol,
gambling, conventional weapons and firearms,
and tobacco.
Values scoring (emphasize companies that
score well in the following areas):
environment, human rights, animal testing,
diversity, labor relations, sexual orientation,
and corporate governance.

name: Horizon Enhanced Socially Responsible
summary: The Horizon Enhanced Socially Responsible strategy is an all-equity enhanced index strategy. Horizon asserts that its Enhanced Socially Responsible strategy can achieve outperformance by applying quantitative overlays to the MSCI KLD 400 Social Index, an index that is selected largely on qualitative characteristics.  The MSCI KLD 400 Social Index is a free float-adjusted market capitalization index designed to provide exposure to U.S. companies that have positive environmental, Social and Governance (ESG) characteristics. The MSCI KLD 400 Social Index consists of 400 companies selected from the MSCI USA Investable Market Index (IMI). The starting universe for the strategy is the MSCI KLD 400 Social Index. Horizon scores each of the 400 stocks in the index using Horizon's proprietary Quadrix stock-rating system. The 40 highest-scoring stocks in the index in terms of Quadrix Overall score (excluding the bottom 2% of index components based on market cap) typically make it into the portfolio. Initial individual positions are approximately equal-weighted and typically held for 12 months, at which time the equity portfolio is rebalanced and reconstituted depending on the results of Horizon's quantitative methodology. Changes to the equities may occur more frequently than annually in the event of takeovers or other corporate actions. For the initial investment selection, no sector can account for more than 25% of the total portfolio. While the portfolio may be 100% invested in stocks, cash and fixed-income investments may be held depending on macro market conditions.

name: Trillium Sustainable Opportunities
summary:
The strategy uses a thematic approach to identify companies addressing
sustainability challenges in three areas: Climate Solutions, Economic
Empowerment, and Healthy Living. A team of fundamental, sector focused
analysts conduct bottom-up financial analysis including a rigorous integrated review of financial and environmental, social, and governance (ESG) factors. The
Investment Management Committee, comprised of portfolio managers and
analysts, meets periodically to review and approve recommendations to the buylist recommended by the analysts. A strategy team, headed by the lead Portfolio Manager, rebalances the portfolio on at least a quarterly basis to identify the best sub-set of names from the buy-list at that particular point of time. The team leverages an optimization process that helps monitor and control portfolio
characteristic exposures while overweighting companies based on a proprietary
alpha score that includes an analyst rating. The portfolio has no fossil fuel
exposure.

summary: Conatus Capital employs a long/short global equity strategy seeking to generate alpha on both sides of the balance sheet. The manager performs intensive bottom-up analysis as the basis for their investment strategy, and invests long and short in businesses for which its understanding of the central drivers is at variance with market expectations and valuation. The manager seeks to obtain insight on the following five areas: (1) Business - returns on invested capital, competitive position and cash generation; (2) Management team - leadership, intelligence, skills, competence, ability, ownership in the company and ethical standards; (3) Key business drivers - sustainable competitive advantage, discontinuous change (i.e. new management, technology or business model) or onset of a new industry cycle; (4) Variant perception - critical insight into factors (e.g., direction, duration or degree) that will cause a business to perform at variance with Wall Street consensus; (5) Valuation - earnings and cash flow 18 to 24 months in the future. The portfolio typically has about 40 to 60 long positions, each representing 1% to 5% of capital at cost and approximately 50 to 70 short positions, each representing 0.5% to 2% of capital at cost. Gross and net exposures generally range from 125% to 200% and 25% to 65%, respectively.

name: Triodos SICAV II Microfinance Fund
summary: The Sub-Fund aims at delivering a full range of financial services to the underserved in developing countries and countries in transition. This includes SMEs as well, which in many countries, still lack access to financial services and specifically credits. The Sub-Fund will realize this by contributing to the development of Microfinance into a fully-fledged and integral part of the financial sector in developing and transition countries. Generally, the investments of the Sub-Fund will be allocated in financial institutions that provide financial services to Micro-entrepreneurs and SMEs. The investment by the Sub-Fund might therefore be in a commercial bank that primarily provides services to SMEs. Such an investment by the Sub-Fund might take place when there is a clear market demand for financial services to SMEs and the commercial bank is best suited to provide these services. The investments of the Sub-Fund will be focused on the following Investees: Microfinance Institutions, other financial institutions and SME banks aimed at providing financial services to low-income people, micro-enterprises and SMEs; Intermediary investment vehicles and funds focused on investments in the Microfinance and Financial Inclusion sector; Holding companies of Microfinance Institutions and/or SME banks; Special Purpose Vehicles for Microfinance Institutions and/or SME banks; Structured notes or other collateralized debt instruments in the Microfinance sector The Sub-Fund will mostly invest, directly or indirectly, in Microfinance Institutions and other applicable financial institutions that have a track record and have gone  55 through the first phase of rapid growth and are financially sustainable. The Sub-Fund can also invest in greenfield Microfinance Institutions. In most cases these institutions will be supervised by relevant local government authorities. The Sub-Fund will invest in Equity, Subordinated debt, Convertible debt, Senior debt, and debt instruments of qualifying investments. The assumed Sub-Fund investment amount per investment project will typically be between EUR 1 million and EUR 10 million, but is bound by the single client exposure and other investment restrictions as provided for in section 5. The Sub-Fund will generally take minority Equity positions in the Investees. The Sub-Fund will mainly invest in non-listed securities and investment instruments other than Transferable Securities. However, the Sub-Fund may also, on an ancillary basis, invest in stock-listed companies. For the temporary investment of liquidity surpluses, the Sub-Fund may invest in Bonds and Money Market Instruments issued by companies, governments or public international bodies admitted to the Triodos sustainable investment universe. The AIFM assesses the sustainability of these instruments on the basis of best-in-class performance and minimum standards. These criteria are based on (i) the degree to which the sustainability of our society is influenced and (ii) the respect of our cultural heritage, animal well-being, ecosystems, human rights, natural resources, social structures and public health. The Equity investments of the Sub-Fund will primarily be in local currency, i.e. any currency other than U.S. Dollars and Euro. For debt financing, the investments will be a mixture of local currency and investments in U.S. Dollars and Euro. Investments in U.S. Dollars will be hedged to a large extent against the Reference Currency of the Sub-Fund (perfect hedges of the interest and principal flows may not be economical). Investments in local currencies may be hedged where possible and deemed appropriate. Cash and liquid assets will be mainly invested in Euro.

name: Knights of Columbus Limited Duration Bond Fund
summary: Under normal circumstances, the Fund invests at least 80% of its net assets, plus any borrowings for investment purposes, in bonds. This investment policy can be changed by the Fund upon 60 days' prior written notice to shareholders. For purposes of this policy, bonds include a variety of fixed-income instruments, such as securities issued or guaranteed by the U.S. Government and its agencies or instrumentalities, municipal bonds, corporate obligations, residential and commercial mortgage-backed securities, and asset-backed securities. The Fund invests primarily in U.S. issuers and investment-grade securities, but may hold securities that are rated below investment grade (high yield or junk bonds). The Fund may invest in securities with any maturity or duration, but seeks to maintain an average duration similar to that of the Barclays Capital 1-3 Year U.S. Government/Credit Index, which generally ranges between zero and three years. Duration measures how changes in interest rates affect the value of a fixed income security. For example, a five-year duration means that the fixed income security will decrease in value by 5% if interest rates rise 1% and increase in value by 5% if interest rates fall 1%. Thus, the longer the duration, the more volatile the security. The Fund makes investment decisions consistent with the United States Conference of Catholic Bishops' Socially Responsible Investing Guidelines (the USCCB Guidelines), and therefore, does not invest in companies involved with abortion, contraception, pornography, stem cell research/human cloning, weapons of mass destruction, or other enterprises that conflict with the USCCB Guidelines. In selecting investments to purchase on behalf of the Fund, the Adviser combines quantitative and qualitative analyses to identify market sectors and individual issuers that the Adviser believes are undervalued in the market. For corporate issuers, the Adviser analyzes the company's financial statements as well as its prospects for future cash generation, while for mortgage- or asset-backed securities, the Adviser analyzes the quality of the underlying receivables and structural credit enhancements.  The Adviser will general sell a security on behalf of the Fund if the security reaches its estimated fair value or is impacted by an adverse event, or if more attractive alternatives exist.

name: Knights of Columbus Small Cap Equity Fund
summary:
Benchmark: Russel 1000

Under normal circumstances, the Fund invests at least 80% of its net assets, plus any borrowings for investment purposes, in equity securities. This investment policy can be changed by the Fund upon 60 days' prior written notice to shareholders. The equity securities in which             the Fund invests are primarily common stocks, but may also include American Depositary Receipts ("ADRs"), which are traded on U.S. exchanges and represent an ownership in a foreign security. The Fund may invest in securities of companies with any market capitalization. Under normal market conditions, the Fund will invest in at least three countries, including the United States, and at least 40% of its assets will be invested in non-U.S. companies, in both developed and emerging market countries. For purposes of this policy, company is considered  to be a non-U.S. company if: (i) 50% of the company's assets are located outside of the United States; (ii) 50% of the company's revenues are generated outside of the United States; or (iii) the company maintains its principal place of business outside of the United  States.The Fund makes investment decisions consistent with the United State Conference of Catholic Bishops' Socially Responsible Investing Guidelines (the "USCCBGuidelines"), and therefore, does not invest in companies involved with abortion, contraception,  pornography, stem cell research/human cloning, weapons of mass destruction, or other enterprises that conflict with the USCCB Guidelines. In selecting investments for the Fund, Boston Advisors, LLC ("BostZn Advisors" or the "Sub-Adviser") combines quantitative and qualitative analyses. The SubAdviser first ranks the individual stocks in which the Fund may invest through the use of models that incorporate multiple fundamental factors, with the weightings of the factors in the models varying in relation to the stock's industry group and the current market environment. The Sub-Adviser then ranks industry groups based on similar fundamental data and macroeconomic considerations, and purchases stocks on behalf of the Fund based on the stock and industry rankings. The Sub-Adviser will generally sell a stock on behalf of the Fund if the stock experiences a rankings decline or extreme price movements, or for risk management purposes.

name: Osmosis Model of Resource Efficiency World ex US
summary: The Osmosis MoRE Japan strategy offers exposure to a basket of resource efficient firms from all economic sectors excluding financials and in Japan only. The portfolio of resource efficient firms are weighted by their inverse economic p/e and rebalanced quarterly. The stocks are systematically selected from 32 industry sectors, Japanese listed stocks only, each stock chosen for inclusion will be ranked in the top quartile of their relative sector based on their MoRE Resource efficiency score. The stocks are then weighted for value based on the economic PE of each company. The portfolio is broadly diversified across sectors excluding financials and has a large cap bias. Portfolio Construction A multifactor resource efficiency score is created for each of the companies within the disclosing universe. Each individual resource factor (energy, water & waste) is denominated by the company's revenues (USD) for the applicable reporting period. Each factor is then normalized relative to its relevant industry peers.

name: Loring Ward Global Porfolio Series Sustainability Balanced
summary:
Benchmark Breakdown:
30% S&P 500, 20% MSCI EAFE (net div), 50% BofAML US Trsy/Agcs AAA 1-3 Yr

The Global Portfolio Series is guided by Loring Ward's Asset Class Investing philosophy, a strategic, asset class investment approach based on the research of some of the academic community's most innovative and respected thinkers and economists. Grounded in the knowledge that asset allocation has the greatest impact on investment returns, Asset Class Investing is designed to carefully control the investments included in each asset class, giving investors truer market returns than similar strategies will. The DFA Funds Global Portfolio Series is built with 4 asset class funds, offered by noted institutional money manager, Dimensional Fund Advisors, and designed to meet the needs of investors looking for investments that serve their environmental and sustainability values and beliefs. The objective of the Balanced portfolio is to provide a balance between capital preservation and growth. It is designed for those who have an average tolerance for portfolio fluctuations. The investment time horizon is typically 5 to 10 years or more.

summary: Knight Mekong Fund is a directional long equity fund, aiming to provide investors with medium to long-term capital appreciation from a managed portfolio of mainly quoted securities on stock exchanges in Mekong Region. summary: The Calvert International Opportunities Fund uses a multi-manager approach to invest primarily in common and preferred stocks of non-U.S. small-cap to mid-cap companies, which it defines as companies whose market capitalization falls within the range of the MSCI EAFE SMID Index at the time of investment. summary: SICM's US Equities strategy undertakes a bottom-up, fundamental approach to large-cap stock selection.  SICM has identified three key sources of investment inefficiency, which the firm aims to address in its approach to investing:  dispersion of analyst skill; risk management; and materiality of environmental, social, and governance (ESG) factors to asset value.  Accordingly, SICM considers the research of only 10% of all sell-side analysts, whom the firm has identified as "skilled," as their recommendations lead to alpha in about 80% of cases.  Further, portfolio construction and risk management seek to maximize the impact of security selection on active risk, and minimize the impacts of other factors, such as industry, geography, and currency.  Finally, SICM integrates ESG factors in stock evaluation as an adjustment on forecasted returns.

name: Horizon Enhanced Christian Values
summary: The Enhanced Christian Values strategy is an all-equity enhanced index strategy. Horizon believes its Enhanced Christian Values strategy can achieve outperformance by applying quantitative overlays to the MSCI USA Catholic Values Index, an index that is selected largely on qualitative characteristics. The 40 highest-scoring stocks in the index in terms of Quadrix Overall Score typically make it into the portfolio. Stocks are typically held for 12 months, at which time the equity portfolio is rebalanced and reconstituted depending on the results of our quantitative methodology. Changes to the equities may occur more frequently than annually in the event of takeovers or other corporate actions. For the initial investment selection, no sector can account for more than 25% of the total portfolio. While the portfolio may be 100% invested in stocks, cash and fixed income investments may be held depending on macro market conditions.

name: Knights of Columbus Large Cap Growth Fund
summary: Under normal circumstances, the Fund invests at least 80% of its net assets, plus any borrowings for investment purposes, in equity securities of large-capitalization companies. This investment policy can be changed by the Fund upon 60 days' prior written notice to shareholders. For purposes of this policy, a large-capitalization company is a company with a market capitalization within the range of the Russell 1000 Growth Index at the time of initial purchase. While the market capitalization range of the Russell 1000 Growth Index changes throughout the year, as of December 31, 2015, the market capitalization range of the Russell 1000 Growth Index was between $718 million and $583.613 billion. The equity securities in which the Fund invests are primarily common stocks of U.S. companies. The Fund makes investment decisions consistent with the United States Conference of Catholic Bishops' Socially Responsible Investing Guidelines (the USCCB Guidelines), and therefore, does not invest in companies involved with abortion, contraception, pornography, stem cell research/human cloning, weapons of mass destruction, or other enterprises that conflict with the USCCB Guidelines. In selecting investments for the Fund, Boston Advisors, LLC (Boston Advisors or the Sub-Adviser) combines quantitative and qualitative analyses to seek to identify companies with above-average growth prospects. The Sub-Adviser first ranks the individual stocks in which the Fund may invest through the use of models that incorporate multiple fundamental factors, with the weightings of the factors in the models varying in relation to the stock's industry group and the current market environment. The Sub Adviser then ranks industry groups based on similar fundamental data and macroeconomic considerations, arankings. The Sub-Adviser will generally sell a stock on behalf of the Fund if the stock experiences a rankings decline or extreme price movements, or for risk management purposes.

name: ValueAct Spring Master Fund, L.P. (the "Spring Fund")
summary: ValueAct's Spring Fund employs an activist-oriented investment strategy, similar to their master fund, that is focused on sustainability related to environmental and social issues around ESG investing. The investment team seeks to identify companies that are out of favor, or may be undergoing significant transitions. Such companies may be temporarily mispriced for a variety of reasons, including perceived unfavorable industry conditions, poor business performance, changes in management or ownership, reorganizations or other external factors.  These conditions can often result in fundamentally "good" businesses that are available at depressed valuations.  The goal in each investment is to work productively with management and/or the company's board to implement a strategy or strategies that maximize returns for all shareholders. The portfolio will be concentrated in the team's top 10 or 15 ideas and will be comprised of predominantly U.S. equities, though the strategy permits investments in private equity and venture capital.

name: Black Diamond SRI Ltd.
summary: Black Diamond Relative Value seeks to identify securities mis-pricings relative to related securities, groups of securities, or the overall market. The fund seeks to exploit the long market bias of most investors, emphasizing appreciation of securities rather than attempting to capture the difference in the performance of two or more securities. Investments may represent short-term or long-term fundamental views on the relative performance of a security. Positions are set up in a hedged construct to isolate discrepancies in value and minimize market risk.

summary:
Ardsley Partners Renewable Energy Fund is a fundamentally driven, long biased equity hedge fund with a bottom-up approach. It is a global equity fund dedicated to the renewable energy/CleanTech sector. The investment objective is to generate capital appreciation by investing principally in equity securities of public companies engaged in renewable energy/CleanTech.The fund utilizes three basic investment styles which focus on the renewable energy sectors from a global perspective. (1) A core investment style that employs fundamentally driven bottom up research to identify specific securities it believes are undervalued. These companies tend to be long-term investments, typically ranging from a year to several years. (2) An opportunistic event-driven style still focusing on the company's fundamentals but taking advantage of near-term events. Positions are traditionally held for approx. 3-9 months. (3) A short-term trading style that takes advantage of market inefficiencies. Typically held for a week or less. Over half of all investments, by dollars invested, are long-term (1yr+), with the remainder split between medium-term (3-9 months) and short-term. 
The Fund typically will include 50-80 positions in total depending on market conditions. Typically, the portfolio holds 50 long positions and 25 short positions. Although there are no set guidelines, the target exposure is 30-100% net long. Leverage is used sparingly, with the highest gross exposure reaching 150% and generally between ~105% and 135%.

name: Matthews Asia ESG Fund
summary: Under normal market conditions, the Matthews Asia ESG Fund seeks to achieve its investment objective by investing at least 80% of its net assets, which include borrowings for investment purposes, in the common and preferred stocks of companies of any market capitalization located in Asia that Matthews believes satisfy one or more of its environmental, social and governance (ESG) standards. The Fund seeks to invest in companies across the market capitalization spectrum that Matthews believes to be undervalued but of high quality and run by management teams with good operating and governance track records. In addition, the Fund seeks to invest in those Asian companies that have the potential to profit from the long-term opportunities presented by global environmental and social challenges as well as those Asian companies that proactively manage long-term risks presented by these challenges.

name: CAM ESG Japan Fund
summary: CAM ESG Japan Fund aims to achieve sustainable growth through investing in ESG-excellent companies. The fund invests in 100 selected japanese companies based on proprietary model which combines ESG-analysis and Financial-analysis. The team stresses that their ESG approach is really a financially motivated one, with the belief that highly scoring ESG companies deliver stronger and more sustainable growth over the long term. To operationalize this view, the team quantifies the integration of ESG factors into company leadership and strategy, blends this score with quantitative financial analysis, and then invest in the top 100 highest scoring companies, weighted by ESG score.

Deferral: \tThe program took effect 11/1/10. \tConsistent with best practices, a portion of the variable compensation (annual discretionary bonus and profit sharing plan) of each team member whose variable compensation is greater than 150,000 is subject to a mandatory three-year deferral. \tDeferral rates of 25% to 45% apply. \tDeferrals are payable at the end of three years, provided the employee remains in good standing. summary: The team's primary universe comprises all names in the strategy's benchmark, the MSCI Emerging Markets Net Index, which covers 23 countries and approximately 836 names as of 6/30/16. However, the team believes that the benchmark does not adequately reflect the opportunities available to investors in emerging markets. Because of this, there are three non-benchmark areas that the strategy may invest in: frontier markets, developed markets that earn a substantial proportion of their revenue from emerging markets and smaller cap stocks that are not captured in the MSCI Emerging Markets Net Index. Frontier Markets: Large, developing, countries such as Nigeria, Saudi Arabia and Vietnam are classified as frontier and have not yet been admitted to the benchmark. Many of these countries exhibit attractive long-term outlooks with strong growth potential and are seemingly emerging markets countries in all but name. Developed Markets: An increasingly important factor is that many emerging market companies are choosing to list in a developed market, and many of these businesses that are listed in developed markets actually derive the bulk of their income from emerging markets. The team finds attractive names in this space. Emerging Market Small Capitalization Companies: There is a significant universe of attractive emerging market stocks that are considered too small to be included in the MSCI Emerging Markets Net Index. In aggregate, the universe available to the team consists of more than 2,000 names. The strategy's maximum out-of-benchmark exposure is 35% of the portfolio. The team believes that the depth and amount of independent research it conducts gives it an advantage when researching out-of-benchmark names. It allows the team to analyze extensively the small cap and frontier names that are often covered by very few (if any) analysts. The team is benchmark agnostic and therefore looks for the best names in the entire emerging market universe (including frontier markets), and not simply names that fall into the benchmark.

This includes understanding the industry dynamics that affect the company's business, management's track record of success, and its approach to corporate governance and shareholder disclosure. This work culminates in a thorough understanding of the company's business model, and an evaluation of its earnings power and the source and sustainability of its competitive advantage. For example, the team has determined that well-managed energy companies require strong environmental, health and safety (EHS) systems in place to operate sustainably, whereas employment and workplace issues are critical for technology companies that seek to maintain and attract talent for the overall sustainability of their business over the long term. Throughout this process, the team simultaneously performs ESG research to seek to identify leadership companies in workplace practices, environmental sensitivity, and community relations. The team believes this extra level of due diligence leads to a more granular understanding of the business and enables the team to better identify good quality, responsible managements. The team's ESG criteria stem from the belief that responsibility is a hallmark of quality. Through in-depth analysis, the team evaluates companies' records with respect to the workplace, community and environment. The team seeks to understand how a company's products and policies affect its stakeholders and society at large. The team recognizes that no corporate record will be 100% positive or 100% negative in all areas of concern and therefore examines the overall direction companies take toward demonstrating leadership and progress in the areas of social and environmental impact. The ESG research is based on both avoidance and leadership parameters. The team searches for companies they believe demonstrate leadership in the environment, community and workplace, including diversity and progressive employment practices. across the firm, effective partnering with clients to achieve goals, risk management and overall investment performance. Neuberger Berman investment professionals on portfolio management teams are paid a fixed base salary and annual discretionary, performance-based bonus, which is a variable portion of total compensation, or on a production model, generally paid on a monthly basis whereby formulaic compensation is paid on a fixed schedule (monthly or quarterly) or a combination of salary, bonus and/or production compensation. The long-term retention incentives include: \tEmployee-Owned Equity. Certain employees (i.e., senior leadership and investment professionals) participate in Neuberger Bermans equity ownership structure, which was designed to incentivize and retain key personnel. Most equity issuances are subject to vesting. \tContingent Compensation. Certain employees may participate in the Neuberger Berman Group Contingent Compensation Plan (the \"CCP\"). Under the CCP, up to 20% of a participants annual compensation in excess of $500,000 is contingent and subject to vesting. Starting in 2017 (and, for some employees, in 2016), participants may elect to have up to 50% of contingent amounts delivered in the form of vested NBSH equity. Further, eligible employees who have represented that they have sufficient direct investments in Neuberger Berman strategies in their private accounts (typically, 50% of their average annual compensation over a three year period) can elect to receive up to 100% of deferred compensation in the form of vested equity. For portfolio managers, contingent amounts under the CCP that are not delivered in the form of NBSH equity are held in a notional account in the teams strategy and a portion may also be held in the Neuberger Berman Portfolio, which is a portfolio of the investment strategies we manage across the firm. Subject to continued employment at the firm and other conditions, a participants contingent amounts maintained in the notional account vest in equal amounts over three years. \tRestrictive Covenants. Most investment professionals are subject to notice periods and restrictive covenants which include non-solicit restrictions. In addition, depending on participation levels, certain senior professionals who have received equity have also agreed to additional notice and transition periods and, in some cases, non-compete restrictions. Through ownership interests and investments in client-facing strategies, senior leaders commit a substantial portion of their personal wealth to the firm. Neuberger Berman is rare among global investment firms in that it is owned by its employees. summary: To pursue its goal, the Fund invests primarily in common stocks of mid- to large-capitalization companies that meet the Fund's social policy. The Fund seeks to reduce risk by investing across many different industries. The Portfolio Managers employ a research driven and valuation sensitive approach to stock selection, with a long term perspective. They look for solid balance sheets, strong management teams with a track record of success, good cash flow and the prospect for above-average earnings growth. They seek to purchase the stock of businesses that they believe to be well positioned and undervalued by the market. Among companies that meet these criteria, the Portfolio Managers look for those that show leadership in environmental concerns, and progressive workplace practices including diversity and community relations.

The SRI version of the strategy overlays exclusionary screens for fossil fuel producers. This strategy generally appeals to pragmatic ESG investors, preferring over/under-weighting of holdings. HIP seeks to outperform traditional investment benchmarks via this strategy, striving to achieve more positive human impact, lower risk, and increased financial returns.

name: Loring Ward Global Porfolio Series SRI Equity
summary:
Benchmark Breakdown: 59% S&P 500, 39% MSCI EAFE (net div), 2% BofAML US Trsy/Agcs AAA 1-3 Yr

The Global Portfolio Series is guided by Loring Ward's Asset Class Investing philosophy, a strategic, asset class investment approach based on the research of some of the academic community's most innovative and respected thinkers and economists. Grounded in the knowledge that asset allocation has the greatest impact on investment returns, Asset Class Investing is designed to carefully control the investments included in each asset class, giving investors truer market returns than similar strategies will. The DFA Funds Global Portfolio Series is built with 5 asset class funds, offered by noted institutional money manager, Dimensional Fund Advisors, and designed to meet the needs of investors looking for investments that serve their social and ethical values and beliefs. The objective of the Equity portfolio is to maximize long-term growth potential. It is designed for those willing to assume a higher level of risk to potentially achieve greater returns. These investors should have a long-term investment horizon and be able to withstand sizable fluctuations in portfolio value. The investment time horizon is typically 20 years or more.

name: LKCM Aquinas Value Fund
summary: The Fund seeks to achieve its investment objective by investing under normal circumstances in equity securities of companies which the Adviser believes to be undervalued relative to a company's earnings. The Adviser's primary strategy in managing the Fund is to select securities that generally have below average price to earnings ratios, lower price to cash flow characteristics, attractive dividend yields and/or lower price to book value ratios than the overall market. The Fund seeks to invest in the equity securities of high quality companies that typically exhibit certain characteristics, including high profitability levels, strong balance sheet quality, competitive advantages, ability to generate excess cash flows, meaningful management ownership stakes, attractive reinvestment opportunities, strong market share positions, and/or attractive relative valuation. These equity securities may include common stocks, preferred stocks, securities convertible into common stock, American Depositary Receipts (ADRs), real estate investment trusts (REITs), rights and warrants. The Fund may invest in equity securities of small, mid and large capitalization companies. The Fund practices socially responsible investing within the framework provided by the United States Conference of Catholic Bishops' Socially Responsible Investing Guidelines (Guidelines). The Fund's investment approach incorporates the Guidelines through a combination of screening portfolio companies based on criteria set forth in the Guidelines, dialogue with companies whose policies and practices conflict with the Guidelines, and/or potentially excluding from the Fund's portfolio the securities of those companies that are unwilling to alter their policies and practices over a reasonable period of time. The Adviser monitors companies selected for the Fund for policies on various issues contemplated by the Guidelines. If the Fund invests in a company whose policies and practices are inconsistent with the Guidelines, the Adviser may attempt to influence the company or sell the company's securities or otherwise exclude future investments in such company.

It also had low scores on business ethics and other governance issues. Although these rankings put Kepco at the bottom 5 percent of the EM portfolio, the Investment Committee and research team believe that it was important to look forward and focus on how a company is resolving these issues. Kepco was sold this year after strong returns following its nuclear capacity factors rising from the low 40's to the mid-70's and is an example of a company the Investment Committee would not exclude despite average ESG scores, as the analyst felt management and the board were taking positive steps to resolve past governance issues. Pacific Rubiales (PRE CN): Pacific Rubiales focuses on the exploration, development and production of heavy, medium and light crude oil primarily in Colombia. A majority of its revenue comes from extracting heavy oil from Colombias eastern fields. Based on historical models and fundamental analysis, Pacific Rubiales is an attractive investment as it holds nearly 70 exploration & production blocks in Colombia. The company grew its production from 34,000 barrels per day to 99,000 barrels per day from 2009 to 2012. Such high production growth raised concerns about its drilling safety practices within the Investment Committee. Yet, the companys independent board and increasing ESG disclosures over that same period helped build the Investment Committees confidence in the drilling practices of the company. According to Sustainalytics, Pacific Rubiales is a top performer in its industry, ranking 1 out of 168 other companies. Its individual E, S and G scores have also improved since 2012, demonstrating good progress in the last two years. Although this company is demonstrating best practices from an ESG perspective, TWI sold the position in late 2014 due to the companys sensitivity to lower oil prices. Indo Tambangraya Megah (ITMG IJ): Indo Tambangraya is a coal mining company based in Indonesia. Historical models have ranked the stock as an attractive investment. However, based on the TWI analysts short-term outlook for the coal industry, the Investment Committee decided against purchasing the stock in TWIs EM portfolio. The Investment Committee anticipated the decline in short-term coal prices due to low natural gas prices in North America and an oversupply of coal in world markets. Indo Tambangrayas low mine life compared to its peers remains a large negative factor in TWIs fundamental analysis due to the ongoing weakness in coal prices. Also, the companys average cash cost for coal mining is above average relative to other Indonesian coal miners. Based on TWIs own ESG assessment, the analyst did not raise any major red flags about the company or its business practices. Indo Tambangraya complies with local governance and also has two independent board members, which is typical for companies that have a majority shareholder. According to Sustainalytics 2014 company report, Indo Tambangraya was an average performer in its industry, ranking 90 out of 168. The company also had not shown any progress in the last two years on its individual E, S and G scores. Although Indo Tambangraya complied with local governance, the company is an average ESG performer and does not appear to stand out in its industry. In this case, the Investment Committee would look to buy a comparably attractive stock that is a better ESG performer in its industry."}, "investment_decision": {"process": {"value": "Integrating ESG Practices into the Investment Process

Step One:
Identify relevant ESG factors impacting the industry, sub-industry or TWI valuation group in question. Sustainalytics should be able to help with an initial list of factors used in each of the eleven GICS1 sectors along with prior knowledge from analysts.

Step Two:
Isolate key ESG factors in the companys business model and measure whether there is an expected material positive or negative impact on revenues-costs and/or assets-liabilities going forward. This will start with reports on the severest controversies (rank 4 and 5) provided by Sustainalytics on their existing holdings as well as additional reports and other sources of information such as Bloomberg and sell-side research on new purchases.

Step Three:
Exclude 4 or 5 controversies from TWI model portfolios unless a written case can be made for continued ownership. These assessments will be provided to clients and consultants upon request. In the case of any exceptions, which are anticipated to be infrequent, TWI is in a position to communicate proactively and get buy-in given the limited number of institutional relationships.

Step Four:
If the existing holding or new purchase candidate has a controversy score of 3 or below, the senior analyst covering the stock will provide the ESG specialist and TWIs Investment Committee a brief one or two paragraph rationale discussing the industry and/or company-specific ESG issues that may be pertinent for ongoing monitoring or potential escalation over the next six-to-twelve months and over the longer-term.

Step Five:
If the existing holding or new purchase has a total ESG score or multiple individual E,S, or G scores from Sustainalytics in the top quartile or higher (typically >70) when compared against the industry peer group and the overall TWI universe, the senior analyst will recommend to the ESG specialist and the Investment Committee whether to increase the position size of the stock in the appropriate model portfolio(s). Conversely, when a company scores in the bottom quartile (typically <40), the senior analyst may also recommend a reduction in the position size or elimination from consideration.", "implementation": "Their ESG specialist will review proactive disclosures of ESG factors that can help companies navigate through regulatory and reputational risks. They believe good mitigation strategies can highlight opportunities for operational efficiency, especially related to environmental impact reduction. Although TWI does not invest based on any explicit top-down or thematic drivers across industries or countries, the analysts will incorporate additional information associated with ESG disclosures and best practices into their initial and ongoing assessment of the stock."}, "oversight_process": "As a relative value manager, TWI may periodically invest in companies that have been assessed to have previously performed badly with respect to ESG criteria, but are now showing signs of improvement. For example, in fall 2013, TWI decided to purchase KEPCO. A state-owned monopoly with an emphasis on nuclear power generation, KEPCO experienced a valuation discrepancy when a bribery scandal hit regarding safety-test certificates. Although the company scored poorly on governance measures at the time, management was taking steps to eliminate corruption issues. This analysis dovetailed nicely with improving fundamentals for the business as the governments interests remained aligned with the firms success at lifting nuclear capacity factors and lowering greenhouse gas emissions through renewables.
When the ESG issue appears significant in shaping an industrys competitive dynamics, but it isnt clear how these dynamics are translated to a companys financials, TWI may allocate a higher or lower weight for a position based on the senior analysts view of the long-term advantage. For example, several of their technology holdings in Taiwan score very highly on environmental and social factors relative to their peers, which has influenced their portfolio weights higher. These factors relate to best practices in light technology manufacturing, waste disposal and workplace safety issues. On the other hand, several consumer and multi-industry companies that they have invested in across China and Southeast Asia may be slower to adopt best practices in ESG and have only become aware of them over the past few years."}, "factor_integration_method": "TWIs main objective is to incorporate sector-specific factors in industry and company ESG analysis. This type of integrated research identifies ESG factors that are expected to be material to a particular sector and incorporates them into valuations and investment recommendations of TWI universe companies. These include aerospace and defense, autos, banks, beverages, building and construction, chemicals, education, electrical equipment, energy, food retail, food products, home and personal (HPC), insurance, media, metals and mining, pharmaceuticals, real estate, retail, semiconductors, technology, telecommunications, transport and utilities. Geographies will include Asia, Australia, Europe, Emerging Markets, and Global including the USA."}

name: Aquilys Global Water and Waste Long Short Equity Master Fund Limited
summary:
Aquilys Global Water and Waste Long Short Equity Fund is a long short equity fund with a long directional bias, investing primarily in global listed equities exposed to the water and waste industry. The Fund believes dislocations between price and value exist within their investment universe and uses bottom-up, fundamental analysis to identify these investment opportunities. The investable universe can be further split in several underlying sectors: 1) Utilities (water, waste or diversified, regulated or non-regulated); 2) Capital Goods; 3) Tech, Bio or Chemicals; 4) Investment, Conglomerates or Holding Company; 5) Design, Engineering & Services companies.
The geographic focus is global although initial exposure will be concentrated on the developed markets in the US and Europe; the rest of the world should account for ~15-20% of the targeted universe. The portfolio typically consists of 30-40 long positions and 10-15 short positions.

name: DFA International Sustainability Core 1 Portfolio
summary: The International Sustainability Core 1 Portfolio is a no-load mutual fund designed to achieve long-term capital appreciation. The Portfolio seeks to purchase a broad and diverse group of securities of non-US companies in developed markets with an increased exposure to small cap companies and those Dimensional considers to be value companies as compared to their representation in the international market universe, while adjusting the composition of the Portfolio based on environmental impact considerations. Dimensional defines the international market universe as a market cap weighted portfolio of non-US companies in developed markets that have been authorized as approved markets for investment by Dimensional. Securities are considered value stocks primarily because a company's shares have a high book value in relation to their market value (BtM). In assessing value, additional factors such as price to cash flow or price to earnings ratios may be considered, as well as economic conditions and developments in the issuer's industry. The criteria for assessing value are subject to change from time to time

name: Triodos SICAV 1 Sustainable Pioneer Fund
summary: Triodos Sustainable Pioneer Fund invests in global equities issued by small and medium-sized listed companies that work to provide pioneering and innovative solutions for sustainability issues. Triodos Sustainable Pioneer Fund selects companies that actively contribute to the development of innovative and sustainable solutions for the future. The fund's focus is on climate protection (sustainable energy), healthy people (medical technology), clean planet (environmental technology) and on companies that are pioneers in terms of corporate social responsibility (CSR) within their sectors. Triodos Research is responsible for the sustainability research and defines the investment universe, based on social and environmental criteria. Delta Lloyd Asset Management is responsible for selecting investments for this fund, within the binding guidelines of our sustainable investment universe.

name: Boston Common Large Cap Core Equity Fund
summary: Boston Common integrates financial and sustainability factors into its investment process because we believe Environmental, Social, and Governance (ESG) research helps us identify companies that will be successful over the long-term. We believe successful investors need to assess a company's fundamentals, or an industrys evolutionin the wider context of economic, environmental, social and financial stability. We seek companies that can capitalize on new market opportunities, implement efficiency improvements, and avoid unanticipated costs stemming from inadequate attention to ESG risks. As a result, we believe ESG research helps improve portfolio quality and financial return potential. As global investors, we have built an extensive network of research sources, NGOs and activist groups to improve our understanding of corporate conduct in all markets. We use our voice on behalf of the Funds shareholders to raise environmental, social, and governance issues with the management of select portfolio companies through a variety of channels. These include dialogue with management, voting proxies in accordance with ESG guidelines, and participation in the annual shareholder meeting process.

name: LKCM Aquinas Small Capital Fund
summary: The Fund seeks to maximize long-term capital appreciation, while incorporating Catholic values investing principles in the investment process. The Fund seeks to achieve its investment objective by investing under normal circumstances at least 80% of its net assets (plus any borrowings for investment purposes) in equity securities of smaller companies. The Fund primarily chooses investments that Luther King Capital Management Corporation (Adviser) believes are likely to have above-average growth in revenue and/or earnings and potential for above average capital appreciation. Smaller companies are those with market capitalizations at the time of investment between $600 million and $4.5 billion. The Fund is not required to sell equity securities whose market values appreciate or depreciate outside this market capitalization range. The Fund seeks to invest in the equity securities of high quality companies that typically exhibit certain characteristics, including high profitability levels, strong balance sheet quality, competitive advantages, ability to generate excess cash flows, meaningful management ownership stakes, attractive reinvestment opportunities, strong market share positions, and/or attractive relative valuation. These equity securities may include common stocks, preferred stocks, securities convertible into common stock, American Depositary Receipts (ADRs), real estate investment trusts (REITs), rights and warrants. The Fund practices socially responsible investing within the framework provided by the United States Conference of Catholic Bishops' Socially Responsible Investing Guidelines (Guidelines). The Fund's investment approach incorporates the Guidelines through a combination of screening portfolio companies based on criteria set forth in the Guidelines, dialogue with companies whose policies and practices conflict with the Guidelines, and/or potentially excluding from the Fund's portfolio the securities of those companies that are unwilling to alter their policies and practices over a reasonable period of time. The Adviser monitors companies selected for the Fund for policies on various issues contemplated by the Guidelines. If the Fund invests in a company whose policies and practices are inconsistent with the Guidelines, the Adviser may attempt to influence the company or sell the company's securities or otherwise exclude future investments in such company.

summary: The GMO Climate Change Fund seeks to deliver high total return by investing globally in companies focused on climate change mitigation and adaptation. Climate change mitigation and adaptation industries include clean energy, batteries and storage, electric grid, energy efficiency, agriculture, water, and companies that service these industries. Stock selection is driven primarily by valuation-based modeling and balances the desire to provide diversified exposure to various climate change segments with the attractiveness of the different segments within the universe. The impacts of climate change are accelerating and the scale is not fully understood. There are risks, including stranded assets, carbon pricing, disruption in auto industry, as well as opportunities associated with climate change. The Fund seeks out companies that will be part of the solution.

name: Martin Investment Global Eco Investing
summary: Martin Investment Management LLC's global Eco-Investing strategy combines the "Best Ideas" Growth with a Value Discipline approach with investing in global businesses that positively impact the environment. This strategy invests in the securities of a variety of corporations that embrace recycling, open space, water purification, and clean energy sources. Martin Investment Management, LLC would consider the following ESG risks and opportunities in the investment decision making: management structure, employee relations, executive compensation, and a company's historic track record or not developing significant liabilities for poor practices in conducting its business. The firm has a commitment to find companies that effectively use resources through governance, conservation, and preservation, and that apply best social and governance principles to their operations. The firm has access to the prohibitive list of countries and governments that do not adhere to best practices.

name: Auriel Absolute Return Fund
summary: Launched in June 2007 the Auriel equity market neutral strategy utilizes a rigorous approach trading the most liquid equities in a long/short, beta and sector neutral portfolio. The objective is to generate absolute returns by managing a diversified, risk-controlled portfolio with a low correlation to traditional asset classes and to the existing hedge fund universe. The focus is on the largest, most liquid, publicly traded equities, which make up approximately 1,000 names, grouped into six regional portfolios. The systematic portfolio construction process is designed to minimise exposure to multiple risk factors to ensure true market neutrality. The research effort is continuous in the search for new insights/anomalies in the global ex. U.S equity markets. Additionally, the best in class portfolio construction and risk management techniques available are used to turn the investment themes into a robust, diversified portfolio. The fund was renamed the Sustainable Absolute return fund to mark our commitment to responsible investing.

summary: Community Capital's Intermediate Fixed Income Separate Account Strategy (Intermediate Fixed Income Composite) is managed against the Barclays U.S. Aggregate Bond Index. summary: SICM's Global Equities strategy undertakes a bottom-up, fundamental approach to large-cap stock selection.  SICM has identified three key sources of investment inefficiency, which the firm aims to address in its approach to investing:  dispersion of analyst skill; risk management; and materiality of environmental, social, and governance (ESG) factors to asset value.  Accordingly, SICM considers the research of only 10% of all sell-side analysts, whom the firm has identified as "skilled," as their recommendations lead to alpha in about 80% of cases.  Further, portfolio construction and risk management seek to maximize the impact of security selection on active risk, and minimize the impacts of other factors, such as industry, geography, and currency.  Finally, SICM integrates ESG factors in stock evaluation as an adjustment on forecasted returns.

name: Knights of Columbus Large Cap Value Fund
summary: Under normal circumstances, the Fund invests at least 80% of its net assets, plus any borrowings for investment purposes, in equity securities of large-capitalization companies. This investment policy can be changed by the Fund upon 60 days' prior written notice to shareholders. For purposes of this policy, a large-capitalization company is a company with a market capitalization within the range of the Russell 1000 Value Index at the time of initial purchase. While the market capitalization range of the Russell 1000 Value Index changes throughout the year, as of December 31, 2015, the market capitalization range of the Russell 1000 Value Index was between $380 million and $439.679 billion. The equity securities in which the Fund invests are primarily common stocks of U.S. companies. The Fund makes investment decisions consistent with the United States Conference of Catholic Bishops' Socially Responsible Investing Guidelines (the USCCB Guidelines), and therefore, does not invest in companies involved with abortion, contraception, pornography, stem cell research/human cloning, weapons of mass destruction, or other enterprises that conflict with the USCCB Guidelines. In selecting investments for the Fund, Boston Advisors, LLC (Boston Advisors or the Sub-Adviser) combines quantitative and qualitative analyses to seek to identify companies that are undervalued in the market. The Sub-Adviser first ranks the individual stocks in which the Fund may invest through the use of models that incorporate multiple fundamental factors, with the weightings of the factors in the models varying in relation to the stock's industry group and the current market environment. The Sub-Adviser then ranks industry groups based on similar fundamental data and macroeconomic considerations, and purchases stocks on behalf of the Fund based on the stock and industry rankings. The Sub-Adviser will generally sell a stock on behalf of the Fund if the stock experiences a rankings decline or extreme price movements, or for risk management purposes.

name: Miller/Howard Rising Dividend Plus
summary: Miller/Howard searches for companies that serve a proven market, favoring enterprises with a repeating-business model that have a demonstrated track record of success. Companies are screened for financial strength at the balance sheet and income statement level, and for conservative accounting practices. A premium is placed on reliability of future company success. Attractive holdings often have some protection against competition through market dominance, branding, geography, or intellectual property. Features such as growth of cash, stock buybacks, insider buying, insider holdings, consistency between revenue and earnings growth, financial reporting transparency, attractiveness as an acquisition, management frankness, sound corporate governance, and corporate community citizenship are important factors in Miller/Howard's overall analysis. The portfolio may contain overweight positions in certain sectors or industries, changing weights in various capitalization sizes, and  as market conditions warrant  greater cash than would be typical of a long-only portfolio. In other words, the portfolio is also characterized by an element of sector rotation, size rotation, and transitional cash.

name: Owl Creek SRI Fund, Ltd
summary: The Owl Creek Socially Responsible Investment Fund (the SRI Fund) employs a global opportunistic value approach, making event-driven investments across many different industries and across all parts of a company's capital structure. Following a socially responsible investment program, the SRI Fund abides by a restricted companies list, avoiding any prohibited companies in which the other Flagship Funds invest. Such companies include those engaged in activities directly related to abortion, fetal stem cell research, the manufacture of contraceptives, pornography, adult entertainment, tobacco, alcohol, gambling, and the production of weapons of mass destruction and landmines. The SRI Fund primarily invests in both long/short value equities and long/short distressed securities. Within both categories, the SRI Fund operates as a bottom-up value investor, searching for undervalued investment opportunities from around the globe. The portfolio consists of names that are facing secular change, regulatory uncertainty, litigation, refinancing risk, fraud and other issues causing negative investor sentiment. The SRI Fund looks opportunistically across both the debt and equity of companies to take advantage of situations from which other investors are shying away due to uncertainty or recent negative events and headlines.

name: Knights of Columbus International Equity Fund
summary: Under normal circumstances, the Fund invests at least 80% of its net assets, plus any borrowings for investment purposes, in equity securities. This investment policy can be changed by the Fund upon 60 days' prior written notice to shareholders. The equity securities in which             the Fund invests are primarily common stocks, but may also include American Depositary Receipts (ADRs), which are traded on U.S. exchanges and represent an ownership in a foreign security. The Fund may invest in securities of companies with any market capitalization. Under normal market conditions, the Fund will invest in at least three countries, including the United States, and at least 40% of its assets will be invested in non-U.S. companies, in both developed and emerging market countries. For purposes of this policy, company is considered  to be a non-U.S. company if: (i) 50% of the company's assets are located outside of the United States; (ii) 50% of the company's revenues are generated outside of the United States; or (iii) the company maintains its principal place of business outside of the United  States.The Fund makes investment decisions consistent with the United State Conference of Catholic Bishops' Socially Responsible Investing Guidelines (the USCCBGuidelines), and therefore, does not invest in companies involved with abortion, contraception,  pornography, stem cell research/human cloning, weapons of mass destruction, or other enterprises that conflict with the USCCB Guidelines. In selecting investments for the Fund, Boston Advisors, LLC (BostZn Advisors or the Sub-Adviser) combines quantitative and qualitative analyses. The SubAdviser first ranks the individual stocks in which the Fund may invest through the use of models that incorporate multiple fundamental factors, with the weightings of the factors in the models varying in relation to the stock's industry group and the current market environment. The Sub-Adviser then ranks industry groups based on similar fundamental data and macroeconomic considerations, and purchases stocks on behalf of the Fund based on the stock and industry rankings. The Sub-Adviser will generally sell a stock on behalf of the Fund if the stock experiences a rankings decline or extreme price movements, or for risk management purposes.

name: Kabouter International SMID-Cap Strategy
summary: Kabouter is a long-only portfolio focused on international non-U.S. small cap equities. The Firm aims to invest in under-appreciated international companies which may benefit from specific secular growth themes. The team identifies prospective investments using a quantitative screening model that seeks to capture stock with high profitability, strong balance sheet, and consistent earnings growth. The investment process then applies fundamental, bottom-up analysis to companies identified by the model, including how they will benefit from one or more secular growth theme. The strategy aims to hold 20 to 40 companies and expects to hold them for three to seven years. The Firm also has a plan for each company to be discovered by the investment community through friendly activism through strategic and M&A advice as well as ESG initiatives.
